<td>Tokyo (the capital of Japan), literally eastern capital</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><a href="/wiki/Kana#Collation" title="Kana">Collation</a> (word ordering) in Japanese is based on the <a href="/wiki/Kana" title="Kana">kana</a>, which express the pronunciation of the words, rather than the kanji. The kana may be ordered using two common orderings, the prevalent <a href="/wiki/Goj%C5%ABon" title="Gojūon">gojūon</a> (fifty-sound) ordering, or the old-fashioned <a href="/wiki/Iroha" title="Iroha">iroha</a> ordering. <a href="/wiki/Japanese_dictionaries" title="Japanese dictionaries" class="mw-redirect">Kanji dictionaries</a> are also collated using the <a href="/wiki/Radical_(Chinese_character)" title="Radical (Chinese character)">radical</a> system.</p>
<div style="width: 12.5em; border: 1px solid #666; text-align: left; float: right; clear: right; margin: 5px 5px 5px 1em; background: white; font-size:small;">
<div style="text-align: center; border-bottom: 1px solid #666;padding: .5em;"><a href="/wiki/File:%E6%9B%B8.svg" class="image" title="Japanese writing"><img alt="Japanese writing" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/%E6%9B%B8.svg/100px-%E6%9B%B8.svg.png" width="100" height="100" border="0" /></a> <b><strong class="selflink">Japanese writing</strong></b></div>
<div style="padding: .5em;">
